05971nam a22008655i 9780824883447DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20202020hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019724877  a97808248834477 a10.1515/97808248834472doi  a(DE-B1597)563417  a(OCoLC)1157077783  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI00aSB87.J3 7aHIS0210002bisacsh04a581.9522231 aHavens, Thomas R. H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLand of Plants in Motion :bJapanese Botany and the World /cThomas R. H. Havens; ed. by Anand A. Yang, Kieko Matteson. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2020  a1 online resource (248 p.) :b23 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPerspectives on the Global Past00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1. East Asia's Plants in Geological Time -- t2. Plants in Early Modern Japan -- t3. Seeking Japanese Plants in Europe and North America -- t4. Foundations of Plant Biology in Modern Japan -- t5. Plant Biology in Japan's Age of Empire -- t6. Plant Biologists in an Era of Specialization -- tNotes -- tSources Cited -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLand of Plants in Motion is the first in any language to examine two companion stories: (1) the rise of an East Asian floristic zone and how the Japanese islands evolved an astonishing wealth of plant species, and (2) the growth of Japanese botanical sciences.The majority of plant species regarded as "Japanese" trace their origins to western China and the eastern Himalaya but are so indigenized that they often seem native today. Early modern scientists in Japan drew on knowledge of Chinese herbal medicine but achieved distinctive insights into plant life commensurate with but separate from their European counterparts. Scholars at the University of Tokyo pioneered Japanese plant biology in the late nineteenth century. They incorporated Western botanical methods but sought a degree of difference in taxonomy while also gaining international legitimacy through publications in English. Japan's age of empire (1895-1945) was less about plant exploration and more about plant collection, for both scientific and economic benefits. Displays of species from throughout the empire made Japan's sphere of colonization and conquest visible at home. The infrastructure for research and instruction expanded slowly after World War Two: new laboratories, botanical gardens, scholarly societies, and publications eventually allowed for great diversity of specialized study, especially with the growth of molecular biology in the 1970s and DNA research in the 1980s. Basic research was harmed by cuts in government funding during 2012-2017, but Japanese plant biologists continue to enjoy international esteem in many fields of scholarship.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aBotanyzJapanxHistory. 0aPlantsxMigrationxHistory. 0aPlantszJapanxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Japan.2bisacsh1 aMatteson, Kieko, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aYang, Anand A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2020 Part 2z978311069629508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishz978311070473008iTitle is part of eBook package: